#: ../../source/concepts/peers.rst:5 ed099fe9f62f43be88bfa52b94214c0b
msgid "Peers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/concepts/peers.rst:7 88e74177fd8b4c4cbf66627dd30ba4b6
msgid ""
"The library widely uses the concept of \"entities\". An entity will refer"
" to any `User <https:://tl.telethon.dev/?q=User>`, `Chat "
"<https:://tl.telethon.dev/?q=Chat>` or `Channel "
"<https:://tl.telethon.dev/?q=Channel>` object that the API may return in "
"response to certain methods, such as `functions.GetUsers "
"<grammers.functions.GetUsers>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/concepts/peers.rst:14 491cc2dba4b047988a079925d751f0b4
msgid ""
"When something \"entity-like\" is required, it means that you need to "
"provide something that can be turned into an entity. These things "
"include, but are not limited to, usernames, exact titles, IDs, `Peer` "
"objects, or even entire `User`, `Chat` and `Channel` objects and even "
"phone numbers **from people you have in your contact list**."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/concepts/peers.rst:20 c0b3ab17ee4e4a659d891b6c2ac0f4f9
msgid ""
"To \"encounter\" an ID, you would have to \"find it\" like you would in "
"the normal app. If the peer is someone in a group, you would similarly "
"`client.get_participants(group) <grammers.Client.get_participants>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/concepts/peers.rst:25 19481618a9214f9ea7b22c32cc66fda6
msgid ""
"Once you have encountered an ID, the library will (by default) have saved"
" their ``access_hash`` for you, which is needed to invoke most methods. "
"This is why sometimes you might encounter this error when working with "
"the library. You should ``except ValueError`` and run code that you know "
"should work to find the entity."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/concepts/peers.rst:33 fda1f740740649edb1e0e2e5a2e995f5
msgid "Contents"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/concepts/peers.rst:36 8c8672b691b5423c8b18bcbc4704249d
msgid "What is a InputPeerLike?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/concepts/peers.rst:38 9b4868fb6fb644e88ab56b677030baaa
msgid ""
"A lot of methods and requests require *entities* to work. For example, "
"you send a message to an *entity*, get the username of an *entity*, and "
"so on."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/concepts/peers.rst:42 ede9c6e1b60449f7a803004b005bdb78
msgid ""
"There are a lot of things that work as entities: usernames, phone "
"numbers, chat links, invite links, IDs, and the types themselves. That "
"is, you can use any of those when you see an \"entity\" is needed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/concepts/peers.rst:48 0f407f738a9f470eac4e0b7acb23865b
msgid ""
"Remember that the phone number must be in your contact list before you "
"can use it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/concepts/peers.rst:51 0320b0d567ea4f988a7749201d389708
msgid "You should use, **from better to worse**:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/concepts/peers.rst:53 aa71514dd34b493d9b67e0010e2d0f06
msgid ""
"Peer. For example, if you had to get someone's username, you can just use"
" ``user`` or ``channel``. It will work. Only use this option if you "
"already have the entity!"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/concepts/peers.rst:57 5c9087b5493d492cad7a87fbe429c0b4
msgid ""
"IDs. This will always look the entity up from the cache (the "
"``*.session`` file caches seen entities)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/concepts/peers.rst:60 8afe57c8646b4d0681eda58c6b271bfc
msgid ""
"Usernames, phone numbers and links. The cache will be used too (unless "
"you force a `client.get_entity() "
"<telethon.client.users.UserMethods.get_entity>`), but may make a request "
"if the username, phone or link has not been found yet."
msgstr ""

